    "summary": "Jericho, located in the Jordan Valley near a perennial spring, is among the oldest continuously occupied settlements on earth. Archaeological work at the site known as Tell es-Sultan has revealed occupation layers extending back to approximately 9500 BCE, making it one of the earliest known permanent human communities. The presence of a reliable water source — the Ain es-Sultan spring — drew hunter-gatherers and then early farmers to this location across thousands of years.\n\nDuring the Pre-Pottery Neolithic A period (c. 9500–8500 BCE), the settlement grew substantially. Inhabitants constructed round mud-brick dwellings and, most remarkably, erected a massive stone tower — [[event:1367|the Jericho Tower]] — and substantial defensive walls [[event:1391|encircling the settlement]]. These structures, built without metal tools, represent some of the earliest monumental architecture anywhere in the world and imply a degree of social organization, surplus labor, and communal planning unprecedented for the period.",
